<Base
  title="Teaching Philosophy"
  description="The teaching philosophy of Gregory Johnson Jr. â€” a student-centered, output-based approach to Spanish built on challenge, comfort, and human connection."
>
  <article class="philosophy">
    <a class="philosophy__back" href="/personal-website/teaching/">
      <span class="arrow" aria-hidden="true">&larr;</span> Teaching
    </a>
    <h1 class="philosophy__title reveal">Teaching Philosophy</h1>
    <div class="philosophy__body prose reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">
      <p>
        A classroom should be a place where every student feels challenged and comfortable at the
        same time. Given the inherently oral nature of language learning, both challenge and comfort
        have to work symbiotically within the relationship between teachers and students. Beyond the
        classic reasons for taking a Spanish class (the second-most-spoken language in the world,
        more opportunities in business or medicine, the long-term cognitive benefits of
        bilingualism), there is something deeper to be found in human connection, something that
        makes university students better equipped for the workforce.
      </p>
      <p>
        After completing a program in any discipline, bachelor&rsquo;s students will find themselves
        in interviews. By that stage, they are usually qualified for the job. The reality is that,
        beyond general knowledge of the position, the real purpose of an interview is to find out
        whether the candidate is someone the firm wants to have around, and those skills are
        developed in the language classroom. At the start of any semester, elementary and
        intermediate Spanish classes fill with fifteen to twenty students, most of them strangers.
        Prompts ask about a student&rsquo;s family, hobbies, favorite foods, and the other ordinary
        parts of life. In being challenged to produce structured output, students are quietly
        building human connections and the comfort to talk about themselves with a room of
        strangers. Those skills, which no transcript can measure, are what I most want my students to
        carry out of my class.
      </p>
      <p>
        To build a classroom that prioritizes oral output and human connection, a flipped-classroom
        philosophy is essential. The acquisition of second-language grammar is still being researched
        thoroughly; we know how students can be guided toward good outcomes, but we have yet to find a
        single, one-size-fits-all methodology. With that in mind, a combination of explicit and
        implicit output should be employed. A flipped classroom lets students take control of their
        learning, each one working through the rules and examples in the way that fits them best.
        Once that work is done outside of class, class time becomes a fifty-minute flood of input
        that calls for structured output and brings interpersonal relationships to life. It is hard
        to speak a language you do not yet know; but when students gain comfort with the material at
        their own pace, they arrive ready to speak.
      </p>
      <p>
        I also firmly believe in the place of healthy competition in the classroom, because I never
        want a student to feel left behind. Although much of the material is acquired at each
        student&rsquo;s own pace, the nature of an output-based classroom, and the connections built
        among peers, creates a natural urgency to keep up with one another, and a quieter competition
        within each student as well. The ideal language learner does not, of course, need a grade at
        the end of the course; but I believe in innovative ways of assessing ability through oral
        exams and in-class writing, which place a productive pressure on students to keep moving
        through the material.
      </p>
      <p>
        To support that competitive, flipped classroom, I believe in bringing technology into every
        lesson. Games are a wonderful way to clear the mind of academic pressure while still flooding
        the experience with input and requiring output to win, and they add to the human connection
        and challenge I want in my classrooms.
      </p>
      <p>
        We are in the middle of another technological revolution, one that is transforming the
        university experience. The evolution of generative AI forces educators and students alike to
        adapt how we approach assignments and exams. I do not
        want my students to feel afraid to use it. Used as a tool rather than a crutch, it can make
        oral output flow more freely. Technology in the classroom has to go beyond a projector and a
        desktop, and my philosophy encourages students to use every tool at their disposal to keep
        the environment both challenging and comfortable. Large language models are not human, but
        they will keep getting better at producing human-like responses. Used well, I believe they
        will only deepen the human connection that student output creates, while assessment keeps
        those responses honestly the students&rsquo; own.
      </p>
      <p>
        My own journey into a second language did not include a flipped classroom or such advanced
        technology. Even so, I promise to keep an innovative and flexible posture in my teaching.
        Using every tool and current line of research to build enriching activities, dynamic
        assessments, and real relationships among my students, I hope they come to feel the same
        desire I did to study and immerse themselves in the Spanish-speaking world. My years abroad
        transformed my worldview. My hope is that a thoughtful use of technology and an
        output-centered, flipped classroom encourage my students to travel, to apply what they learn,
        and to come away with a deeper cultural understanding of the language, better prepared for
        whatever discipline they pursue beyond Spanish.
      </p>
    </div>
